Task 2: Mini exploratory report on juvenile showshoe hares in Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest

By: Claire Gonzales

November 10, 2021

1. Project Overview

Bonanza Creek LTER is part of the US Long Term Ecological Research Network. See more information about the site here. In this mini exploratory report, you will explore the counts and sizes of juvenile snowshoe hares recorded from 1998 - 2012.

2. Data and Analysis

Full metadata can be found at the following URL: https://portal.edirepository.org/nis/metadataviewer?packageid=knb-lter-bnz.55.22

3. Initial Juvenile Hare Investigation

3a. Annual juvenile hare trap counts

Figure 1. Number of juvenile snowshoe hares that were captured within the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest between the years 1999 and 2012. (Data: Kielland et. al., 2017)

The capture data above (Figure 1) reflect that the amount of juvenile snowshoe hares captured was highest in the year 1999 (n = 126) and steadily decreased over time. In total, 378 juvenile snowshoe hares were captured throughout the project duration (1999 - 2012) and the mean yearly capture was 126 \(\pm\) 35.9 (mean \(\pm\) sd). However, it is important to note that this capture data is dependent on how many traps are set out. To account for this, future projects should set out the same amount of traps each year or list results as a percentage of number of hares captured per number of traps deployed annually.

3b. Juvenile hare weight visualization

Figure 2. Comparisons of body mass values (grams) juvenile snowshoe hares captured at Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest between the years 1999 and 2012. Female snowshoe hares are in left pane, followed by male snowshoe hares (middle pane) and hares for which sex was not collected (right pane). Each pane contains body mass measurements for juvenile snowshoe hares captures at each site (Bonbs, Bonmat, and Bonrip). Capture observations from each site are further described with a box plot. The boxs middle black line represents the median values, while the outsides of the box represent the 25th and 75th percentile values. The black dot represents the mean value of observations. (Data: Kielland et. al., 2017)

The data above (Figure 2) reflects that the body mass (g) measurements of male juvenile snowshoe hares had slightly larger mean and median values compared to those measurements made for female juvenile snowshoe hares. In general, these data contain very few outliers, with only one positive outlier for female observations at the Bonrip site and one negative outlier for male observations at the Bonbs site. Notably, the heaviest snowshoe hares for both male and female measurements were captured at the Bonrip site. Conversely, the highest mean and median values were in the Bonbs site across sexes. Few hares could not be sexed and all of those observations (NA; right pane) were constrained to Bonmat and Bonrip sites.

3c. Juvenile weight comparison (male & female snowshoe hares)

Table 1 Shows a summary statistics table for body weight distribution with respect to sex of juvenile snowshoe hares captured in Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest between the years 1999 and 2012. (Data: Kielland et. al., 2017)
Sex Mean (g) Standerd Deviation (g) Count
Female 855.4 292.3 200
Male 945.9 333.2 163
NA 614.5 357.6 15

The body weight (g) distribution of female (n = 200) and male (n = 163) juvenile snowshoe hares depicted in Table 1. The difference in means between weights of male and female snowshoe hares is 90.47 (g), with a small effect size (Cohens d = -0.2904674). Despite this, the difference in means is significant (Welchs two-sample t-test: t(325.02 = -90.47, p = 0.007).

3d. Relationship between juvenile weight & hind foot length

Figure 3 Visualization of initial relationship between body mass (g) with hind leg length (mm) of juvenile snowshow hares captured in Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest between the years 1999 and 2012. (Data: Kielland et. al., 2017)

The relationship between snowshoe hare body mass (g) and hind foot length (mm) is fairly linear across sex and site (Figure 3.). In exploring this more, the simple linear regression reflected that hare body mass loosely predicts length of hind foot (p < 0.001, R2 = 0.299). If all other factors remain constant, on average we would expect hind foot length to increase by 0.031mm per 1g increase in body mass (slope = 0.031mm/g). Body mass (g) and hind foot length (mm) of juvenile snowshoe hares have medium-positive and significant coorelation (Pearsons r = 0.55, p < 0.001). Lastly, diagnostic plots (not included) revealed normally distributed residuals, but residuals were fairly heteroscedastic. This is a concern in using this linear regression to draw conclusions about the population.

4. Summary of Results

This initial exploration of the data reflected the following results:

  • The amount of juvenile snowshoe hares captured was highest in the first year of the project (1999) and has decreased over time.
  • Male juvenile snowshoe hares weigh more than females do, across all sites and with very few outliers. The difference is significant, but the effect size is small.
  • The relationship between body mass and hind foot length of juvenile snowshoe hares is medium-positively and positively correlated. Therefore, if all other factors remain constant, on average we would expect hind foot length to increase by 0.031mm per 1g increase in body mass.

Next steps:

  • Standardize data across all years that hares were captured to determine how many hares were captured compared to the amount of attempts made.
  • Investigate multiple linear regressions that could describe how body mass and other potential variables (e.g.sex or site) could impact hind foot length.
  • Alternately, select more focused variables to remove heteroscedasticity in linear regression model.
